aa(lp74
VThree years later, I found out how wrong I was.
p75
aVBut this time, I was the patient.
p76
aVDespite exercising three or four hours every single day,
p77
aVand following the food pyramid to the letter,
p78
aVI'd gained a lot of weight and developed something
p79
aVcalled metabolic syndrome.
p80
aVSome of you may have heard of this.
p81
aVI had become insulin-resistant.
p82
aa(lp83
VYou can think of insulin as this master hormone
p84
aVthat controls what our body does with the foods we eat,
p85
aVwhether we burn it or store it.
p86
aVThis is called fuel partitioning in the lingo.
p87
aVNow failure to produce enough insulin is incompatible with life.
p88
aVAnd insulin resistance, as its name suggests,
p89
aVis when your cells get increasingly resistant
p90
aVto the effect of insulin trying to do its job.
p91
aVOnce you're insulin-resistant,
p92
aVyou're on your way to getting diabetes,
p93
aVwhich is what happens when your pancreas
p94
aVcan't keep up with the resistance and make enough insulin.
p95
aVNow your blood sugar levels start to rise,
p96
aVand an entire cascade of pathologic events
p97
aVsort of spirals out of control that can lead to heart disease,
p98
aVcancer, even Alzheimer's disease,
p99
aVand amputations, just like that woman a few years earlier.
