aa(lp108
VBut most important, I was left
p109
aVwith these three burning questions that wouldn't go away:
p110
aVHow did this happen to me if I was supposedly
p111
aVdoing everything right?
p112
aVIf the conventional wisdom about nutrition had failed me,
p113
aVwas it possible it was failing someone else?
p114
aVAnd underlying these questions,
p115
aVI became almost maniacally obsessed
p116
aVin trying to understand the real relationship
p117
aVbetween obesity and insulin resistance.
p118
aa(lp119
VNow, most researchers believe obesity
p120
aVis the cause of insulin resistance.
p121
aVLogically, then, if you want to treat insulin resistance,
p122
aVyou get people to lose weight, right?
p123
aVYou treat the obesity.
p124
aVBut what if we have it backwards?
p125
aVWhat if obesity isn't the cause of insulin resistance at all?
p126
aVIn fact, what if it's a symptom of a much deeper problem,
p127
aVthe tip of a proverbial iceberg?
p128
aVI know it sounds crazy because we're obviously in the midst
p129
aVof an obesity epidemic, but hear me out.
p130
aVWhat if obesity is a coping mechanism
p131
aVfor a far more sinister problem going on
p132
aVunderneath the cell?
p133
aVI'm not suggesting that obesity is benign,
p134
aVbut what I am suggesting is it may be the lesser
p135
aVof two metabolic evils.
