aa(lp137
VYou can think of insulin resistance as the reduced capacity
p138
aVof our cells to partition fuel,
p139
aVas I alluded to a moment ago,
p140
aVtaking those calories that we take in
p141
aVand burning some appropriately and storing some appropriately.
p142
aVWhen we become insulin-resistant,
p143
aVthe homeostasis in that balance deviates from this state.
p144
aVSo now, when insulin says to a cell,
p145
aVI want you to burn more energy
p146
aVthan the cell considers safe, the cell, in effect, says,
p147
aV"No thanks, I'd actually rather store this energy."
p148
aVAnd because fat cells are actually missing most of
p149
aVthe complex cellular machinery found in other cells,
p150
aVit's probably the safest place to store it.
p151
aVSo for many of us, about 75 million Americans,
p152
aVthe appropriate response to insulin resistance
p153
aVmay actually be to store it as fat, not the reverse,
p154
aVgetting insulin resistance in response to getting fat.
